A circle passes through the point $(0,1),$ and is tangent to the parabola $y = x^2$ at $(2,4).$  Find the center of the circle.

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

real parab (real x) {
  return(x^2);
}

draw(graph(parab,-3.5,3.5));
draw(Circle((-16/5,53/10),13*sqrt(17)/10));

dot((0,1));
dot("$(2,4)$", (2,4), E);
[/asy]

inference:
The slope of the tangent line to $y = x^2$ at $(2,4)$ is $2x = 4,$ so the tangent line has equation $y - 4 = 4(x - 2),$ or $y = 4x - 4.$  The center of the circle lies on the perpendicular bisector of the segment connecting $(0,1)$ and $(2,4),$ which has slope $-1/4.$  The midpoint of this segment is $(1,5/2),$ so the perpendicular bisector has equation $y - 5/2 = -1/4(x - 1),$ or $y = -x/4 + 11/4.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

real parab (real x) {
  return(x^2);
}

draw(graph(parab,-3.5,3.5));
draw(Circle((-16/5,53/10),13*sqrt(17)/10));
draw((-3,0)--(3,0));
draw((0,-1)--(0,10));
draw((0,1)--(2,4));
draw((-1,-1)--(5,9),dashed);

dot((0,1));
dot("$(2,4)$", (2,4), E);
dot((-16/5,53/10), S);
dot((1,5/2));
[/asy]

Solving the system
\begin{align*}
y &= 4x - 4, \\
y &= -\frac{x}{4} + \frac{11}{4},
\end{align*}we find $x = \frac{16}{5}$ and $y = \frac{53}{10}.$  Hence, the center of the circle is $\boxed{\left( \frac{16}{5}, \frac{53}{10} \right)}.$

